Between 14 June and 31 December 2019, will the World Health Organization confirm a case of Ebola outside the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) and Uganda? Aid workers were killed this week in DRC. Protocol could break down resulting in cross border infections.

A UN World Health Organization press report released today 28 Nov 2019 says that 4 Ebola responders have been killed and 5 other people are reported injured in attacks in the eastern DRC near bordering nations. While the attacks are not responsible for causing Ebola they may create psychological problems for responders and administrators and complicate their security. You can find news about the attacks on the Web at France 24 and offician UN WHO site. Event happens at a moment when outbreaks seems to have quieted down somewhat.

Much noise coming out of Tanzania about "international conspiracy". And yet others report that, indeed, a positive testing by the Tanzanian National Heath Lab came back on the doctor who died in Dar Es Salaam. This person had returned from Uganda and had traveled around in Tanzania before falling ill. There are unofficial reports back to WHO telling of quarantined individuals and other suspected cases in Tanzania. Locales or numbers affected are not publicly known. The government is said by WHO to have been "slow" to work with WHO, or to perform/release confirmatory tests. Finally it was reported 10-5-19 that both Rwanda and Kenya put mobile screening stations at one or more well-traveled entry points they have with Tanzania......
Starting to question what it will take for WHO to confirm a case...

Tanzanian President John Magufuli is cracking down on dissent and is restricting access to information. A new law criminalizes the distribution of information that contradicts the government. Historically it is possible for outbreaks to occur beyond bordering countries but more likely in countries that directly border the affected country.

One new reporting (and death) in Uganda Aug 29 - after a long period of no new incident reportings in Uganda WHO, in its Sep 6 report, says 186 confirmed cases in the prior 21 days - seems to be steady at 75 new per week. In mid-August - spread was found in Kivu province - the third DRC province affected. Rwanda closed its border briefly on Aug 1. Despite the increase in cases, continued open borders and transit with DRC cities has not led to cross-border spread, adjacent or otherwise. Slight revisions to probability in the hopes that the matter remains contained to the DRC.

highly contagious virus, therefore a good possibility that it will move outside the two currently affected nations. the WHO is present and working to control so also well possible that is does not spread. lack of infrastructure is both a blessing and a curse (less chance of quick transmission but also less ability to bring workers and medicine).

Counties bordering Congo s/b aware not to travel (wealthy) unprotected and/or are poor enough where travel isn’t something they are able to do. Also countries bordering Congo should have similar biological conditions and if Ebola hasn’t developed yet, see it as more unlikely to develop as head into seasonal changes.

fluid borders means virus can leak across..... however it's a fairly violent and self-limiting virus in that it presents quickly enough to lift spread. Whilst no one should say 'never' the pathology of the virus and current precautions put some brakes on spread - especially over long distances. You'd need to travel rapidly across border following infection to present in another country...and so far outbreaks have not been close to borders, other than DRC /Uganda border.

Ebola has an incubation period between 2-21 days so it’s easy for an area that has lots of free movement for people to spread the disease. I think given that the WHO is having difficulty tracking all the patients makes it likely that it will spread beyond borders, but may be some time before retrospective analysis has been done to confirm outbreaks. Given that this disease is politically sensitive and may be kept quiet.
International efforts seem to be picking up and making some progress as well as I can tell.

this is the second major outbreak in recent history, and social awareness and medical expertise is very high. vaccines are being teted, with some success. futhermore, the spread of infectious disease such as ebola is well tracked and air travel is the most likely way for the virus to jump to countries not bordering DRC and Uganda. given that the outbreak has been raging for a long time now, i suspect that the airports are well monitored. that leaves land or water based travel. these methods are slow and people infected with ebola are likely to show symptoms and be stopped before reaching a non-bordering country.

I have no knowledge to bring to this question, other than reading a bit of newspaper coverage. From what I know of health systems in the area, It seems at least reasonably plausible that the disease will spread.

The latest cases were detected in Goma, which is a central hub for millions of people moving across East Africa. Goma is located near the Rwandan border. However, foreign workers from both Uganda and Rwanda (which border the DRC) can travel to Kenya (which doesn't border the DRC) freely (provided work documents are valid). Rwanda is itself a very small country and a poor nation. Most people travelling abroad are likely to be job seekers / employees in Kenya. Uganda, on the other hand, is a large country and new cases may be detected there or brought to Kenya via Uganda. Geographically, the disease seems to be spreading northeastwards in the current outbreak (towards more affluent countries), therefore it may be less likely for the disease to spread westwards.
Mighty vaccines are on the way before Ebola will spread by that time.
DRC a battle zone in places so there's a risk of spread but previous experience of outbreak has provided NGOs with good data and best practices on containment. I could be horribly wrong though...
They seem to control it well, but there is alot of people movement across borders where there is no control.

The epidemic has already touched multiple cities. I expect it to spread further since it's pretty hard to restrain people moving around. Lack of trust and instability may also undermine treatment and prevention campaign There's also the chance of a new epidemic declaring itself in west africa where the virus seems to be endemic (last episode 2016)

People could travel out of the DRC to neighboring countries, however, ebola's source is not limited to that region. A separate case could be reported in countries outside of DRC's immediate borders. Thus, the most likely scenario is there are cases in the DRC region and away from the DRC. But, with a vaccine going to trials and ongoing health education in the region could limit the disease, but likely not enough to stop it occuring outside of the DRC by the end of the year.
It is possible that because of air travel someone who has just been infected might travel a large distance. Also this is given that there is a shortage of the unlicenced vaccine.

As the question only asked for one case outside of Uganda that is more probable than "an epidemic," Politically the country has violent uprisings and displaced people. People who are desperate eat bushmeat which is a vector for infection and animals cross borders spreading it elsewhere. Geographically DRC is surrounded by many countries and touches on the ocean and has lake/river boundaries that ease transportation. There are also cross-border sister cities (e.g., Kinshasa and Brazzaville). While it doesn't spread until contact with bodily fluids is made (https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/transmission/index.html) in a warzone it is conceivable that acts of rape or murder will expose persons to the virus more readily. Attacks on treatment centers further encourage such spread not to mention reducing the population of willing first responders and supplies for treating the virus. Culturally the region is known for burial practices that require intimate contact with the body and thus with the body fluid vectors (https://www.socialscienceinaction.org/resources/key-considerations-burial-funeral-mourning-practices-equateur-province-drc-2/). In the 2014 epidemic (https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736%2814%2961828-6/fulltext) an estimate for risk of 2-3 travelers per month via airplane...that outbreak had about 28,000 infected and this one is smaller so far at 2338 (although the number increased by 40 over 5 days according to news reports. We can hope that the new vaccine and treatments will be effective but the question involved just one person getting out to a noncontiguous country. War, politics and fear produce refugees (http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/01/refugees-flee-drc-uganda-escalating-ebola-fears). If Uganda closes its border/slows down border crossings to reduce spread the refugees will head in other directions and other countries. Frightened people are creative, persistent and reactive, particularly if there is no trust in authorities.

- Potential fast spread of Ebola has been shown during the 2015 West Africa Ebola outbreak. Containment of the current outbreak in DRC is made more difficult by the current conflict; a fact with which the worst hit countries in 2015 did not have to contend. There has also been a steady upward trend of cases since Aug 2018 and peaking in May 2019. - Despite this, eleven months on, the areas most at risk are still the northern most parts of North-Kivu, which borders only Uganda. Fruthermore, even if the response is challenging and inadequate, it has scaled-up in the last months through the creation of treatment centers. lodgings and support to survivors.

DRC is surrounded by other countries and the ebola cases appear to be spread out. Add in the political chaos and people trying to get away from the conflict and the disease and it seems inevitable someone with the disease will make it out. As animals spread it as well, they are not bound by borders. In addition the country has outlets on a lake/river and the ocean, an easy way to spread the disease (https://geology.com/world/africa-satellite-image.shtml). Past history (https://www.cdc.gov/vhf/ebola/history/distribution-map.html) shows a wide dispersion of ebola events. Burial customs of intimate contact (https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/SSHAP_burial_funeral_and_mourning_practices.pdf) as well as strong desire to be buried in homelands exacerbate the problems. This April 2019 WHO report (https://www.who.int/csr/don/11-april-2019-ebola-drc/en/) indicates that the management of this outbreak is facing problems in resources and capacity to isolate patients. The only contraindication for spread is that compared to other diseases it is slow to spread (http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/special/health/how-ebola-spreads/?noredirect=on)...it takes 9 to 15 days for 1 person to infect 2...I note the numbers jumped from 2297 to 2338 in just 5 days. The question wasn't focused on how many would get the disease, just if one person might in another country, bordering and not bordering. Finally, in the last major outbreak there were several people who, via air flight, made it to other countries before showing symptoms. The theory of complexity (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complexity_theory) explains how we mis-focus our fight against disease on treating everyone rather than focusing on the few who spread it via multiple social contacts. A part of that theory (the 6-degrees of separation phenomena [more likely a few more than that] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Six_degrees_of_separation ) shows that we are all much closer than we think-- it takes a relatively few relationships to be connected to one of the victims.
